est:<remote-url-hash>#1284`, or\n  `gitbutler-review:<review-id>`\n- change key material: canonical bytes/text for the GitButler change id\n\nHash branch, review, and change key material before embedding it in GitMeta key\nnames. Keep the readable canonical value in `observed_targets` and the\nenvironment snapshot.\n\nFor file paths, store relative paths plainly on the capture turn snap\n[TRUNCATED]\nn API or product flow, they should mean\n\"this session is relevant to this target\", not \"this session generated this\ntarget.\"\n\nGitButler's multiple-branches-in-one-worktree model is the main argument for\nturn-scoped precision. A single agent session can mostly build one feature\nbranch while a specific turn produces a bugfix that the user sends to another\nbranch. Whole-session association is therefore useful but not always precise\nenough for review sharing.\n\nRecommended shape:\n\n- store sessions as the durable transcript object\n- start with derived read-time association results from capture turn evidence\n- let capture turn evidence highlight or filter the relevant part of the session\n- keep existing explicit target-to-session links as stronger evidence if they\n  already exist\n- allow future relationship metadata to carry optional turn scope if an explicit\n  API/product flow needs durable links\n\nIn other words, capture turn scope should refine a session relationship. It\nshould not move transcript ownership onto branches, changes, commits, or pull\nrequests.\n\n## Persist Or Recompute\n\nThe capture turn layer could be stored directly, or some of it could be\nrecomputed from existing records and Git state.\n\nReasons to persist capture turns:\n\n- preserves exact capture boundaries\n- preserves repository state at the time of capture\n- supports later association even after branches or worktree state changed\n- makes handoff and review timelines cheaper to query\n\nReasons to recompute some association:\n\n- avoids prematurely committing to a wrong relationship\n- keeps durable metadata smaller\n- allows better algorithms later without rewriting old data\n\nMy current take: persist the observation, not the conclusion. Store capture turn\nobjects and environment snapshots. Use them to compute association results at\nread time. Persist relationships only if an explicit API/product flow later\nneeds durable links.\n\n## Access Patterns\n\nThe model should make these reads efficient.\n\nDefine the read surface around the two product use cases:\n\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T05:13:24.350Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}